SSH provides
   for algorithms that provide authentication, key agreement,
   confidentiality, and data-integrity services.

The hostname is always in US-ASCII (as per RFC1033);
         internationalized hostnames are encoded in US-ASCII as
         specified in RFC 3490.

The server could require both password and public key authentication;
   however, this requires the client to expose its password to the
   server (see the section on Password Authentication below.)

The transformation between elliptic curve points and
   octet strings is specified in Sections 2.3.3 and 2.3.4 of [SEC1];
   point compression MAY be used.

This document is concerned with SSH implementation details;
   specification of the underlying cryptographic algorithms and the
   handling and structure of X.509v3 certificates is left to other

This document is concerned with SSH implementation details;
   specification of the underlying cryptographic algorithms is left to
   other standards documents.

